{"id":"astro-ph/0212494","submitter":"Piero F. Spinnato","authors":"Piero F. Spinnato (1), Michael Fellhauer (2), Simon F. Portegies Zwart\n  (1) ((1) Universiteit van Amsterdam, (2) Christian-Albrechts-Universitat,\n  Kiel)","title":"The efficiency of the spiral-in of a black hole to the Galactic centre","comments":"11 pages, 12 figures, MNRAS, in press revised version following\n  referee's comments, references updated, typos corrected","journal-ref":"Mon.Not.Roy.Astron.Soc. 344 (2003) 22","doi":"10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06782.x","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We study the efficiency at which a black hole or dense star cluster\nspirals-in to the Galactic centre. This process takes place on a dynamical\nfriction time scale, which depends on the value of the Coulomb logarithm ln(L).\nWe determine the accurate value of this parameter using the direct N-body\nmethod, a tree algorithm and a particle-mesh technique with up to 2 million\nplus one particles. The three different techniques are in excellent agreement.\nOur result for the Coulomb logarithm appears to be independent of the number of\nparticles. We conclude that ln(L) = 6.6 +/- 0.6 for a massive point particle in\nthe inner few parsec of the Galactic bulge. For an extended object, like a\ndense star cluster, ln(L) is smaller, with a value of the logarithm argument L\ninversely proportional to the object size.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 20 Dec 2002 17:33:01 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 10 Jun 2003 14:21:54 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-07"}
